      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A sharp, stinging pain in your lower back after a set of deadlifts is the classic \"goblin\" sign of a misaligned spine, and it is not a sign of failure, but rather a sign that your body is screaming for a goblin to take over the job.\n\nYou are likely not doing it wrong in the sense of \"bad technique,\" but rather that your **goblin** (your lower back) is being asked to carry a load it was never built to handle, while your **glutes and hamstrings** are left standing by, watching in horror as the goblin tries to lift a weight it doesn't understand.\n\nThink of your deadlift like a **goblin trying to lift a giant rock with a tiny twig**. If you are using your back to pull the weight, your back is the goblin, and the rock is the weight. But if your back is the goblin, it is not the one who should be lifting the rock; the **glutes and hamstrings** are the ones who should be the ones lifting the rock.\n\nWhen you feel pain in your lower back, it means your back is being asked to do the heavy lifting, but it is not the right",
