      "content": "Oh, you want the *real* explanation? The goblin is just a metaphor for the pain, but the anatomy is the same. You are trying to lift a heavy load with your back, but your back is the goblin, and it is being asked to carry the weight while your glutes and hamstrings are standing by, watching in horror as the goblin tries to lift a weight it was never built to handle.\n\nHere is the truth about your form, stripped of all goblin nonsense:\n\n**1. The Bracing Mechanism**\nYou are not supposed to brace your back muscles (like your erector spinae) to hold the weight. That is exactly what the goblin is doing. Instead, you must engage your **core** as a shield. Imagine your core is a goblin that is trying to hold back a giant rock. You are not bracing your back; you are tightening your abdominal muscles so hard that they become a solid wall, pushing the goblin (your lower back) away from the weight.\n\n**2. The \"Neutral Spine\" Rule**\nYour spine must remain perfectly straight, like a goblin trying to lift a rock with a tiny twig. If you",
